WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:20.480
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: OK, I think
we're ready to resume.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:27.260
The final program this afternoon
deals with Section 117 and 109.

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:31.230
And the topic is we'll be exploring
whether current limitations on

00:00:31.230 --> 00:00:34.430 position:56%
and exceptions to copyright
protection adequately address issues

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:36.970
concerning software
embedded in everyday products

00:00:36.970 --> 00:00:40.450
or whether amendments or
clarifications would be useful.

00:00:40.450 --> 00:00:44.170
I'd like to start with just
sort of a general observation

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:47.770
from having reviewed
all the comments.

00:00:47.770 --> 00:00:49.800
And while this is not
a universal statement,

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:52.820
it does seem to be
fairly common that many

00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:57.580 position:56%
of the commenters either said that
no changes were warranted or needed,

00:00:57.580 --> 00:01:02.660
on the one hand, and others
commenter said that the same thing

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:06.160
but qualified it by
saying that Sections 109

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:11.810
and 117 properly construed,
no changes are needed.

00:01:11.810 --> 00:01:16.260 position:56%
While that creates the appearance of
consensus, I suspect that somewhere

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:19.320
in the middle there is
some level of disagreement

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:22.010
which hopefully we'll
get into this afternoon.

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:25.690
So, I would throw that out as
sort of an opening question,

00:01:25.690 --> 00:01:30.290
a general question of whether
changes are needed or not,

00:01:30.290 --> 00:01:36.450 position:56%
and if so-- if changes are needed
in the interpretation of 109 or 117,

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:42.500
what those areas of interpretation
where they would be helpful.

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:46.740
So perhaps we could start with 109
if anyone would like to jump in.

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:49.440
Jonathan? Jonathan Band, rather.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:50.740
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Sure.

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:57.500
So, I guess, you know, the sort
of like the threshold issue of,

00:01:57.500 --> 00:01:59.830
you know, properly interpreted--

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:02.560
but, you know, properly
interpreted--

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:05.990
you know, if I were an
Article 3 judge, you know,

00:02:05.990 --> 00:02:08.140
the world would be very
different, but that's--

00:02:08.140 --> 00:02:10.780
I don't see that happening
any time soon.

00:02:10.780 --> 00:02:18.320
And I think especially for
ORI, we're very focused

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:26.170
on the specific problem of
109A and how would applies

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:33.820
to software-enabled products.

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:39.730
And it seems that between the--

00:02:39.730 --> 00:02:47.010
what is an owner and what is the
proper scope of interpretation

00:02:47.010 --> 00:02:51.210 position:56%
of 109A and all of these contractual
issues that we talked about,

00:02:51.210 --> 00:02:52.880
the fact that you could just--

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:55.630
regardless of how courts
interpret 109A,

00:02:55.630 --> 00:03:00.510
you could still have contractual
restrictions on transfer.

00:03:00.510 --> 00:03:03.460
So we just think as
a practical matter,

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:08.240
the only way in the
foreseeable future to really deal

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:10.370
with this issue, you know,
and that's why you have--

00:03:10.370 --> 00:03:12.550
with circuit splits
and all the rest is

00:03:12.550 --> 00:03:16.360
to have something very
short and sweet like YODA.

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:18.480
And that would, you know,

00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:24.970
it wouldn't obviously solve the
entire problem but it would solve,

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:27.270
you know, one piece of the problem.

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:31.450
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: Mr. Perzanowski?

00:03:31.450 --> 00:03:32.750
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: Yes,

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:35.980
I would agree that YODA
is an important first step

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:39.100
and does embody some
important principles.

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:43.150
I would also agree that it
doesn't solve the whole problem.

00:03:43.150 --> 00:03:52.420
I think-- I would not recommend
any changes to the text of 109

00:03:52.420 --> 00:03:56.840
or 117 relevant to
the particular set

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.200
of questions that we're addressing.

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:06.310
Today, what I do think would
be useful is a definition

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:12.860
in Section 101 of owner for
exhaustion purposes, right?

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:18.900 position:56%
Owner of a copy as it appears in 109
and 117 or definition of transfer

00:04:18.900 --> 00:04:24.790
of copy ownership, I think
that is a crucial question.

00:04:24.790 --> 00:04:31.730
It is a question that courts have
answered in a lot of different

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:36.210
and I think inconsistent
ways over the years.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:42.810
I think a definition of ownership
would provide some much needed

00:04:42.810 --> 00:04:44.110
clarity, right?

00:04:44.110 --> 00:04:45.410
Who are we talking about here?

00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:48.550
We're talking about
consumers for the most part.

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:51.820
How do consumers know whether
they own the things that they buy?

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:56.270 position:56%
I don't think it's a particularly
satisfying answer to tell them well,

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:59.700
you know, here's a dozen cases
decided by the Ninth Circuit

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:02.400
and the Federal Circuit
and the Second Circuit

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:05.120
and maybe you can make
sense of this question.

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:07.780
It's really fundamental question

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:12.500
and so I think it deserves some
attention here in terms of what

00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:16.990
that definition would look like.

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:21.350
You know, if it were up to me, I
would have a definition that said

00:05:21.350 --> 00:05:24.890
that anytime you had a
transaction that was characterized

00:05:24.890 --> 00:05:28.920
by a one time payment
and perpetual possession

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:34.350
that is a transfer
of ownership, right?

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:40.520 position:56%
So, that I think is the key
question that we have to answer here

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:43.670
with respect to 109 and 117.

00:05:43.670 --> 00:05:51.390
I also included in my written
comments a couple of references

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:56.110
to the Canadian and Israeli
Copyright Acts and the way

00:05:56.110 --> 00:05:59.500
that they deal with
the ROM copy doctrine

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:05.450
and temporary instantiations
of works transient copying.

00:06:05.450 --> 00:06:10.820
I think there might be some benefit
from clarification there as well.

00:06:14.790 --> 00:06:19.080
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: Mr. Band
mentioned the Your Own Devices Act

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:21.990 position:56%
and suggested that would be a good--

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:26.650
I think Mr. Perzanowski said
it was a good first step.

00:06:26.650 --> 00:06:31.810
What affect or impact if any do--
does anyone anticipate from--

00:06:31.810 --> 00:06:36.790 position:56%
if that legislation was passed, what
impact would it have on innovation

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:42.510
in the field of software for
embedded software for devices?

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:46.470
Mr. Kupferschmid?

00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:51.400
&gt;&gt; Keith Kupferschmid: So
I think if the YODA bill

00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:56.790
or something potentially similar
