of the two would have that effect.

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:28.190
&gt;&gt; Sy Damle: So, can I ask--
sorry, just a general--

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:31.050
which maybe other people
can address which is--

00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:32.390
which I've always just
been curious about,

00:09:32.390 --> 00:09:39.300 position:56%
but why the essential copy exemption
is limited to owners of the copies

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:41.410
and why that's not automatically?

00:09:41.410 --> 00:09:47.340
So, CONTU recommended that Congress
adopt a rule that's, you know,

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:49.140
allows you to create essential
copies if you were the--

00:09:49.140 --> 00:09:51.240
I think it was a lawful
possessor of the copy

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:53.340
and that was changed in
Congress to be owner.

00:09:53.340 --> 00:09:56.000
I'm just wondering just
as a practical matter,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:01.580 position:56%
what's the rationale for limiting
the essential copy defends to owners

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:05.120
of software rather than
anyone who is, you know,

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:08.390
has a lawful possession
of the software?

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:10.410
Mr. Bergmayer?

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:13.420
&gt;&gt; John Bergmayer: I'm
happy to address that.

00:10:13.420 --> 00:10:18.670
Well, as I look at the
essential step copy doctrine

00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:21.930
as really making the most sense
and doing the most useful work

00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:26.950 position:56%
in the case of installing software,
which doesn't happen as much anymore

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:29.720
since people just typically just
installed over the internet.

00:10:29.720 --> 00:10:34.360
But if you have a disk I would
say when you are installing--

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:37.550
you're installing from floppy
disks or a CD-ROM on to a computer,

00:10:37.550 --> 00:10:42.200 position:56%
well that is a copy, right, and I
think that is inarguably a new copy.

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:46.520
And if you own that disk, then
you should be able to use it

00:10:46.520 --> 00:10:47.860
by installing it on a computer.

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:49.840
I mean, I don't think that's a
particularly controversial point

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:52.160
and that's where I think that the
essential step doctrine does the

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:53.460
most useful work.

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:56.340
Where I have sort of
trouble with it is the notion

00:10:56.340 --> 00:11:00.680
that simply using software
creates a ROM copy

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:04.860
and using the essential step
test in that context, I think is,

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:06.990
it shouldn't be necessary to--

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:10.930
either those ROM copy should
be ephemeral and just excluded

00:11:10.930 --> 00:11:15.100
from the definition of copy or
some other doctrine should say

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:19.010
that the possessor in that
context should not need to use--

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:23.690
need a license simply to use the
software, but I think limiting it

00:11:23.690 --> 00:11:28.330
to the lawful owner is logical in
the case of installing software

00:11:28.330 --> 00:11:31.590
because otherwise, I could take
software and then install it

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:34.330
on my computer and I'm the
lawful possessor then I lend it

00:11:34.330 --> 00:11:36.640
to my friend, my friend
is the lawful possessor

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:38.870
because he is borrowing
it and he can install it

00:11:38.870 --> 00:11:40.170
in his computer and so on.

00:11:40.170 --> 00:11:44.580
So I think that limiting it to
owner in that particular concept--

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:49.240 position:56%
contexts makes sense but not in the
context of ROM copies which I need--

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:54.930
I think needs to be more
fundamentally dealt with.

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.230
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: Can I add?

00:11:56.230 --> 00:11:57.530
&gt;&gt; Erik Bertin: Sure.

00:11:57.530 --> 00:11:58.830
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski:

00:11:58.830 --> 00:12:00.130
I think another point that's
important here is to keep in mind

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:01.850
that the owner of a copy stands

00:12:01.850 --> 00:12:05.160
in a special relationship
to the work, right?

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:07.280
The owner of a copy is someone

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:12.990 position:56%
who in the ordinary circumstance
has compensated the copyright holder

00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:16.130
for that work, right?

00:12:16.130 --> 00:12:20.930
And so it makes sense to extend
a set of rights to owners

00:12:20.930 --> 00:12:25.380
that we don't extend, certainly
to the public generally, right?

00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:28.670
Owners have rights that the
public at large shouldn't have.

00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:32.480 position:56%
And there might be other people who
are temporarily in lawful possession

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:35.790
of a copy that we don't think
deserve those protections, right?

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.560 position:56%
So, you know, I order some software,

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:42.030 position:56%
I don't know what decade this
hypothetical takes place in but we--

00:12:42.030 --> 00:12:44.100
I order some software
over the internet

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:46.530
and it gets delivered
to me by FedEx.

00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:49.590
FedEx is in lawful
possession of that software.

00:12:49.590 --> 00:12:51.600
I don't think they get
to make copies of it even

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:54.630
if they're essential to running the
program because they don't stand

00:12:54.630 --> 00:12:57.630
in that sort of relationship
with the copyright holder.

00:12:57.630 --> 00:13:05.100 position:56%
You know, the exhaustion is premised
in large part on this idea of,

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:08.640
you know, the single recovery
theory where, you know,

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:11.050
copyright holders have
been compensated

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:15.780
and as a result some rights
get transferred to consumers.

00:13:15.780 --> 00:13:18.970
That's just not true for people who
might be, you know, like I said,

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:21.090
you know, temporarily in possession

00:13:21.090 --> 00:13:24.180
or bailed users something
along those lines.

