than if you don't-- other than
to really say, I don't agree.

00:55:56.690 --> 00:55:59.920
I'm having trouble finding
a court case that agrees.

00:55:59.920 --> 00:56:04.290 position:56%
And there are lots of people who
have invested lots of time and money

00:56:04.290 --> 00:56:08.520 position:56%
and effort on particular
constructions of that very provision

00:56:08.520 --> 00:56:11.430
that has been shown to
be an enormous success.

00:56:11.430 --> 00:56:13.910
I think it would be unwise

00:56:13.910 --> 00:56:17.780
to disrupt those expectations
or that performance.

00:56:17.780 --> 00:56:20.690
&gt;&gt; Eric Bertin: Mr. Band?

00:56:20.690 --> 00:56:23.660
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Band: Yeah, I
don't see YODA or something

00:56:23.660 --> 00:56:28.480
like that having any impact at
all on open source software.

00:56:28.480 --> 00:56:30.770
As we heard before, you know,

00:56:30.770 --> 00:56:35.790
the open source licenses are
affecting the rights attaching

00:56:35.790 --> 00:56:42.760
to the software but not the copy
of the software because it's--

00:56:42.760 --> 00:56:48.960
and so, you know, the open source
license allows the second user

00:56:48.960 --> 00:56:54.630 position:56%
to make copies or to make derivative
works, those are concluded different

00:56:54.630 --> 00:56:56.670
from what we're talking
about in YODA which is purely

00:56:56.670 --> 00:57:02.460
about can the first person sell
the product to the second person?

00:57:02.460 --> 00:57:07.220
And it doesn't-- and it
would no way limit what's--

00:57:07.220 --> 00:57:11.380
how the open source
model would work.

00:57:11.380 --> 00:57:19.360
But also just getting back to the
previous colloquy about, you know,

00:57:19.360 --> 00:57:21.400
let's say firmware
that is transferred

00:57:21.400 --> 00:57:24.410
from one device to a newer device.

00:57:24.410 --> 00:57:29.610
I mean, you see that all the
time with refurbished products.

00:57:29.610 --> 00:57:33.440
And, you know, we think
that, that secondary market

00:57:33.440 --> 00:57:37.370
for refurbished products is--
I mean that's a good thing.

00:57:37.370 --> 00:57:42.580
It's positive for consumers
because, you know, you have--

00:57:42.580 --> 00:57:45.130
consumers are able to buy
a product at a lower cost

00:57:45.130 --> 00:57:50.030
than they would have been able to
buy a new or unrefurbished product.

00:57:50.030 --> 00:57:55.620
And it's, you know, environmentally
good to recycle products.

00:57:55.620 --> 00:58:00.890
And, you know, so yes it
means it conceivably means

00:58:00.890 --> 00:58:04.300
that you'll have a manufacturer
who would have to compete

00:58:04.300 --> 00:58:08.720
with a refurbished
product but, you know,

00:58:08.720 --> 00:58:13.540
we think that competition is
good basically that in copyright

00:58:13.540 --> 00:58:18.560
and other statutory monopolies are
the exception to the general rule

00:58:18.560 --> 00:58:20.700
in our economy that we want
to promote competition.

00:58:20.700 --> 00:58:24.410
And so, having refurbished
product is a good thing

00:58:24.410 --> 00:58:28.510
and we should encourage
it as much as possible.

00:58:28.510 --> 00:58:31.150
&gt;&gt; Eric Bertin: Mr. Perzanowski?

00:58:31.150 --> 00:58:33.910
&gt;&gt; Aaron Perzanowski: So
I want to go back to--

00:58:33.910 --> 00:58:40.670
to go back a few minutes to a point
that was made about the possibility

00:58:40.670 --> 00:58:46.900
that at least some license
agreements grant consumers' certain

00:58:46.900 --> 00:58:50.000
rights that might otherwise be

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:56.450
within their control
as owners of copies.

00:58:56.450 --> 00:58:58.270
There are circumstances, right,

00:58:58.270 --> 00:59:02.900
where a license does
provide something a keen

00:59:02.900 --> 00:59:06.880
to the rights under
109 or 117, right?

00:59:06.880 --> 00:59:10.840
That happens out in
the world sometimes.

00:59:10.840 --> 00:59:13.380
And, you know, I think that's--

00:59:13.380 --> 00:59:19.150
those kinds of flexible
licenses are a welcome addition

00:59:19.150 --> 00:59:22.420
to what we see out
there in the market.

00:59:22.420 --> 00:59:29.210
You know, so Amazon for example
has a sort of simulation of lending

00:59:29.210 --> 00:59:30.660
that works on the Kindle.

00:59:30.660 --> 00:59:35.470
So publishers can opt in for
some books to allow consumers

00:59:35.470 --> 00:59:40.400
to lend an ebook one time
for a period of two weeks

00:59:40.400 --> 00:59:42.840
and then never again, right?

00:59:42.840 --> 00:59:45.940
And so there are I think two
important limitations to keep

00:59:45.940 --> 00:59:49.970
in mind and I think
demonstrate why those kinds

00:59:49.970 --> 00:59:53.500
of licensed secondary markets
are a pretty poor substitute

00:59:53.500 --> 00:59:54.800
for the real thing.

00:59:54.800 --> 01:00:00.830 position:56%
One is they are incomplete, right,
Amazon system for example is opt in.

01:00:00.830 --> 01:00:04.930
Not all platforms do this certainly
not all publishers participate,

01:00:04.930 --> 01:00:10.520
so you get this sort of spotty
set of rights for consumers.

01:00:10.520 --> 01:00:14.140 position:56%
And the other I think more important
big picture thing is there's a big

01:00:14.140 --> 01:00:18.370
difference between granted
permission to engage in a behavior

01:00:18.370 --> 01:00:21.590
and having a right to engage
in that behavior, right?

01:00:21.590 --> 01:00:25.350
Property is not having
to ask for permission

01:00:25.350 --> 01:00:27.230
and that's why we care
about ownership.

01:00:27.230 --> 01:00:30.320
And there are some really
important things that flow

01:00:30.320 --> 01:00:33.180
from unregulated property
interest, right,

01:00:33.180 --> 01:00:35.480
unregulated secondary markets.

01:00:35.480 --> 01:00:40.470
We might think that those uses
are most variable precisely

01:00:40.470 --> 01:00:44.920
where permission is not
going to be granted, right?

01:00:44.920 --> 01:00:47.650
So, you know, you mentioned that,
you know, sometimes they say,

01:00:47.650 --> 01:00:49.670
look yeah, you can sell your
software but like, you know,

01:00:49.670 --> 01:00:53.710
write down who you're selling it
to and keep track of that transfer.

01:00:53.710 --> 01:00:56.100
Well, you know, one of
the great things that come

01:00:56.100 --> 01:01:00.280
from unregulated unlicensed
secondary markets is privacy.

01:01:00.280 --> 01:01:02.540 position:56%
No one keeps track of who owns what.

01:01:02.540 --> 01:01:05.770
No ones keeps track of what books
you're reading, no one keeps track

01:01:05.770 --> 01:01:07.070
of what software you're using

01:01:07.070 --> 01:01:10.700
and I think consumers
see that as a benefit.

01:01:10.700 --> 01:01:14.130
And you can think about user
innovation or, you know,

01:01:14.130 --> 01:01:18.390
potentially competitive
uses that or, you know,

01:01:18.390 --> 01:01:21.530
competitive resale markets
where it's really unlikely

01:01:21.530 --> 01:01:25.190
that anybody is going to
give permission for someone

01:01:25.190 --> 01:01:28.310
to take their product and build
on it and do something new

01:01:28.310 --> 01:01:34.360
and interesting within where you
might not see permission to sell

01:01:34.360 --> 01:01:38.960
or use product at a lower price
that competes with the new product.

01:01:38.960 --> 01:01:43.690 position:56%
But that's precisely what a property
interest allows owners to do.

01:01:43.690 --> 01:01:48.220
So, those things do exist but
they are not a perfect substitute

01:01:48.220 --> 01:01:52.440
for actual ownership by purchasers.

