01:06:38.380 --> 01:06:40.630
Just a couple of remarks
in regard to the harm

01:06:40.630 --> 01:06:44.940
from the proposed contract
preemption concept.

01:06:44.940 --> 01:06:46.630
I'd like to point out that commonly

01:06:46.630 --> 01:06:50.370
in the business-to-business
context licenses are the result

01:06:50.370 --> 01:06:54.700
of face-to-face arm length
negotiations and the preemption

01:06:54.700 --> 01:06:57.510
of those contracts introduces
unnecessary uncertainty

01:06:57.510 --> 01:07:00.130
into the market place
and is inconsistent

01:07:00.130 --> 01:07:02.310
with the basic free market approach

01:07:02.310 --> 01:07:04.540
of the US Copyright System
dating all the way back

01:07:04.540 --> 01:07:07.640
to Article 1, Section 8, Clause 8.

01:07:07.640 --> 01:07:11.210
In any event, what
this issue really boils

01:07:11.210 --> 01:07:15.940
down to is preempting contract
terms that some people don't

01:07:15.940 --> 01:07:19.860
like not withstanding the fact that
they're enforceable contract terms.

01:07:19.860 --> 01:07:24.400
So it's about government
banning certain business models

01:07:24.400 --> 01:07:27.170
which will actually have
the predictable effect

01:07:27.170 --> 01:07:28.820
of increasing prices

01:07:28.820 --> 01:07:32.970
because software companies
have fewer options and how

01:07:32.970 --> 01:07:37.960
to tailor a license to particular
uses and they're be forced

01:07:37.960 --> 01:07:43.360
to offer higher level,
higher price licenses.

01:07:43.360 --> 01:07:47.610
And the case for government
control in place

01:07:47.610 --> 01:07:50.800
of free market approach
simply hasn't been made.

01:07:50.800 --> 01:07:57.480
The evidence is scant at best
particularly on the context

01:07:57.480 --> 01:08:01.900
of software industry which
is as dynamic as competitive

01:08:01.900 --> 01:08:05.290
and as innovative as any
industry in the Untied States.

